{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491376","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491376"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:44:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:44:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"925"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"925","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/925"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.45,0.06,0.17,0.21]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"925"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51992"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"925","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/925"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"925"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37300"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1717"},{"type":"tags","id":"2076"},{"type":"tags","id":"9022"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"284"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15071"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51992","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/51992"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a six-hour history of spontaneous painless loss of vision in his right eye. He has never had eye problems before. He has a medical history of a myocardial infarction three months ago and placement of a drug-eluting stent. His medications include clopidogrel and aspirin. On examination, his blood pressure is 176/86 mmHg. A retinal view of his affected eye is shown (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate immediate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pilocarpine drops","Digital ocular massage","Anterior chamber paracentesis","Intravenous methylprednisolone","Timolol drops"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis presentation and fundoscopic findings add up to a diagnosis of \u003Cstrong\u003Ecentral retinal artery occlusion (CRAO)\u003C/strong\u003E, almost certainly the result of platelet embolisation from a carotid artery plaque. The patient has a history of vascular disease and the retina has a pale (ischaemic) appearance with the macula maintaining its colour (\u2018cherry red spot\u2019) because of its pigments and adjuvant blood supply.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECRAO is an ocular emergency and partial recover can occur if the ischaemia is reserved in less than four hours.  Immediate treatment should start with \u003Cstrong\u003Edigital ocular massage\u003C/strong\u003E. Digital ocular massage can facilitate disintegration of a thrombus or help disperse a centrally-lodged embolus. This is often given together with intravenous acetazolamide to reduce intraocular pressure.  \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther non-invasive treatments include hyperbaric oxygen, anticoagulation and systemic steroids. Invasive procedures include laser embolectomy, \u003Cstrong\u003Eanterior chamber paracentesis\u003C/strong\u003E and intra-arterial thrombolysis could be second-line treatment. The aim of the treatments is to improve blood flow and to increase the blood oxygen content.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous methylprednisolone\u003C/strong\u003E may be considered if CRAO is secondary to arteritic CRAO which is typically caused by giant cell arteritis.  This is less likely in this case of a patient who likely has atherosclerosis.  Intravenous methylprednisolone may also be considered if primary management options failed.  Digital ocular massage should be attempted first before considering intravenous methylprednisolone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPilocarpine\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Etimolol\u003C/strong\u003E are used in the treatment of glaucoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOngoing management looks at management of the risk factors similar to the management for atherosclerosis with diet and lifestyle changes. Other risk factors include haematological conditions (sickle cell disease, leukaemia, hypercoagulable states), Fabry disease, giant cell arteritis, systemic lupus erythematosus and polyarteritis nodosa.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Digital ocular massage can provide first-line help in the management of central retinal artery occlusion."],"references":["Cugati S, Varma DD, Chen CS, Lee AW. Treatment Options for Central Retinal Artery Occlusion. Cur Treat Opt Neuro 2013;15:63-77. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3553407/","Madike R, Cugati S, Chen C. A review of the management of central retinal artery occlusion. Taiwan J Ophthalmol. 2022 Aug 18;12(3):273-281.  Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC9558462/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37300"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"925"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15575"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15575","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15575"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/a286814a-fd99-4cf0-bb4a-4d239bc72a37.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/a286814a-fd99-4cf0-bb4a-4d239bc72a37.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":437}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37300","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/37300"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-01T15:38:35+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-01T15:39:14